@flexiarg t3/feedback-activation-loop
@title Visible Impact
@sigils [🔁/促]
@audience programme-leads, evaluators, trainers
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/architectural-pair
@see t3/co-ownership-engine, t3/participatory-evaluation
@next t3/participatory-evaluation
@tier architecture
@confidence high
@npt-domain 4.2 Communal Appraisal
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  The programme learns because feedback is structured, visible, and shared. Where feedback mechanisms are thin — optional surveys yielding only positive or absent responses, informal signals like reading the room — the programme lacks evidence of its downstream impact, cannot systematically improve, and cannot make the case for institutional support.

  + context: Trainers note that engagement and feedback are crucial for improving delivery and sustaining motivation, but current mechanisms provide almost no usable signal; cross-institutional sharing channels exist but go unused.
  + if: You want long-term impact and evidence of cultural change beyond one-off sessions.
  + however: Reliance on optional surveys misses signal; trainers lack feedback on impact and cannot easily demonstrate reach; the absence of a feedback loop means the programme cannot learn or justify itself to institutional stakeholders.
  + then: Establish a lightweight feedback loop: short post-session pulse, 3-6 month follow-up, and a visible impact log. Pair this with a rotation of "impact stories" that travel across cohorts.
  + because: Regular feedback sustains motivation, reveals adaptation needs, supports accountability, and — crucially — generates the evidence base that justifies institutional investment in the architectural conditions the programme needs.
      + mechanism: Frequent, low-friction feedback plus shared impact stories builds momentum and surfaces improvement needs early; visible impact evidence creates a case for institutional support.
      + counterfactual: If feedback is limited to optional end-of-course surveys, impact remains invisible, motivation erodes, and the programme cannot argue for the workload allocation and institutional backing it needs.
      + applies-when: Trainers report low survey response and lack of evidence about reach; institutional stakeholders ask for impact data.
      + does-not-apply: Programmes with robust, continuous evaluation already in place.
      + signals: Trainers cannot point to concrete impact; rely on "nobody says this was terrible" as evidence; formal sharing channels unused.
      + evidence: "I have no other ways of getting feedback short of people filling in the feedback form" (T2B); "As we get like a few answers and nobody says this was terrible, I generally think it's gone quite well" (T2B); "Even if you don't get the feedback survey, you can kind of tell whether people are engaged" (T2B). COM-B: "effects are being measured" M=3.35 (lowest item across all waves); T3 follow-up M=3.17 (still lowest at 6 months).
  + next-steps:
      - Add a two-question pulse survey after each session.
      - Run a quarterly impact story round-up shared across cohorts.
      - Pilot participatory evaluation design (see t3/participatory-evaluation).
  + governance:
      - practice: review impact logs in quarterly audits.
      - metric: proportion of sessions with structured feedback; proportion of trainers submitting at least one impact story per year.
